# Distribution-First Idea Validation (audience before product)

## Intent

Pick the next product by mining an audience you already own (or are growing), not by guessing market need.

## Scope

Pick the next product by mining an audience you already own (or are growing), not by guessing market need. Done = signed waitlist + paying pre-orders before line 1 of code.

## Stages

### 1. Mine the audience

Pull demand straight from your own people.

Tasks:
- Read 100 recent replies, DMs, support tickets
- Cluster pains into 3-5 themes
- Pick the densest theme

Outputs:
- Reply review log
- Pain themes
- Top theme

Decision gate: Advance only when one theme has >=10 distinct demand signals.

### 2. Frame the bet

Write a one-liner the audience will repeat.

Tasks:
- Write the bet as a tweet-length one-liner
- Test it in a private DM round
- Iterate until repeatable

Outputs:
- Bet one-liner
- DM feedback
- Iteration log

Decision gate: Advance only when 3 friends can repeat the one-liner.

### 3. Public hypothesis tweet

Float the bet publicly to widen signal.

Tasks:
- Post the bet as a hypothesis tweet
- Tag the segment
- Track replies, follows, and likes by ICP

Outputs:
- Public hypothesis post
- Signal counts
- ICP-tagged engagement

Decision gate: Advance only with >=20 ICP signals.

### 4. Pre-sell page

Ask for money before code.

Tasks:
- Build a single-page Stripe pre-order
- Position price for early-bird
- Link in profile + newsletter

Outputs:
- Pre-order page live
- First receipts
- Profile + newsletter link

Decision gate: Advance only with >=3 paid pre-orders in 7 days.

### 5. Waitlist + cohort plan

Convert the spike into a launch cohort.

Tasks:
- Open a free waitlist alongside paid pre-orders
- Plan a small cohort launch window
- Pre-write the kickoff email

Outputs:
- Waitlist signups
- Cohort plan
- Kickoff email

Decision gate: Advance only when waitlist + paid pre-orders combine to a viable first cohort.

### 6. Build OR refund decision

Use the pre-order data to commit.

Tasks:
- Read the signal honestly
- Decide: build or refund
- Communicate the decision

Outputs:
- Decision doc
- Refund or build comms
- Customer notes

Decision gate: Cycle closes when decision is communicated.

## Common pitfalls

- Skipping the decision-gate write-up to keep moving - closes the loop with vibes, not evidence.
- Treating each stages outputs as optional - every output is a gate input for the next stage.
- Letting one bad week stretch a fixed-cadence ritual into a quarterly one.

## Quality checklist

- Every stage has at least one referenced methodology that resolves under `knowledge/`.
- Every output is a real artefact, not a feeling.
- The final decision is a written commitment, not we will see.
